{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558868/1945092001/0225.xml":{"full_text":"4\nFORECAST u iftit QL A. Serr\u00abd Br Umed Wlr\u201c\nt htmirttrm ijiLLiTPtttttit \u00a9isit*\nUUIUIUU14 4 ^4*44 U 4444444 4 V44 .jhe\n_ 4^r State and National New\nVOL. 78.\u2014NO.270. __WILMINGTON, N, C., THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 20, 1945_ _ESTABLISHED 1867\nDetroit Oil\nStrike Ties\nUp Stations\nUAW FURTHER PLANS\nSlotor City Bus Service\nFacef Stoppage Over\nGasoline Supplies\nDETROIT, Sept. 19\u2014 (/P)\nXhe labor troubles of the na\ntion\u2019s automotive capital\nmounted today as the United\nAutomobile Workers (CIO)\ncontinued preparations for a\nhead-on collision with the car\nindustry over a 30 per cent\nwage increase demand.\nThreatening to add to the 80,000\nin aroa hv wnrk\naiiww;\nstoppages and shutdowns was a\nspreading strike in the oil indus\ntry by the Oil Workers Union\n(CIO) and a curtailment of elec\ntrical equipment to three divisions\nof General Motors Corporation.\nWilliam S. Bullock, general man\nager of Detroit\u2019s municipally own\ned public transportation system,\nsaid only a four days supply of\ngasoline remained for the city\u2019s\napproximately 1,400 buses in daily\noperation.\nThe oil strike began with a stop\npage by truckers, later spread to\nworkers in the Socony Vacuum\nCompany plant in suburban Tren\nton, and was reported affecting\nnearby refineries supplying the\nDetroit area. A 30 per cent wage\nincrease demand ivas involved in\nthe dispute.\nIndustry circles heard reports\nthat as many as 25,000 workers\nin the Chevrolet, Buick and Olds\nmobile divisions of General Motors\nmight be forced into idleness this\nweekend by a strike at the War\nren, Ohio, plant of the Packard\nElectrical Co. The company sup\nplies wiring systems for the three\nGeneral Motors divisions.\nGeneral Motors officials here\nwould not comment.\nThe new threats to the automo\nbile industry\u2019s reconversion\ncame as Richard T. Frankensteen,\nDAW vice president and candidate\nfor Mayor of Detroit at the No\nvember election, reported prog\nress in personal efforts to get 4,500\nKelsey-Hayes Wheel Co. employes\nback at work. The Kelsey-Hayes\nA cruet 9.3 nr*\u00bbpini\ntated the closing of the Ford plants\nand the laying off of 50,000 work\ners.\nThe Ford company listed the\nSocony-Vacuum Co. oil strike\namong 15 other labor disturbances\nin supplying plants that impeded\ncar production. The gasoline short\nage also was reflected in the emp\nty tanks of many gasoline service\nstations. Many of them posted\nsigns, \u201cNo gasoline.\u201d\nWhile management maintained\nits policy of silence concerning the\n30 per cent wage demands, word\ncame from the UAW-CIO that the\nfirst petitions to the National La\nbor Relations Board for a strike\nvote\u2014that among the 325,000 em\nployes in General Motors\u2019 135\nplants\u2014might be filed this week.\nIt previously had been announc\ned a similar petition would be filed\non behalf of upwards of 80,000\nChrysler Corporation employes by\nSeptember 25, and that the UAW\nNational Ford Council would con\nsider like action on behalf of 109,\n000 Ford workers at a meeting\nhere September 29 and 30.\nFrankensteen stepped into the\nKelsey-Hayes strike controversy at\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 2)\nDAVIS RESIGNS\nECONOMIC OFFICE\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 19\u2014 UP)\nPresident Truman tonight apcept\ned William H. Davis\u2019 resignation\njjiuuuiuu;\nin a letter which took the sting\nout of the President\u2019s indirect crit\nicism of Davis yesterday.\nAt his news conference yester\nday a reporter asked the Presi\ndent about a statement attributed\nto Davis that the administrator\nfavored an increase of 50 per cent\nin wages without any accompany\ning rise in prices. The Presidenl\nsaid Davis was not speaking foi\nthe administration.\nIn his letter to Davis, made pub\niic by the White House late in the\nday, after Davis had paid a cal\nthere earlier, Mr. Truman said:\n\u201cI have seen the transcript o:\nyour recent press conference, ac\ncounts of which occasioned some\nmisunderstanding. The transcrip\nitself shows that the true purpor\nof your discussion was to expresi\nthe hope and confidence that th(\neconomic policies already adopte<\nby the government would lead thi\ncountry to the high level of pro\nduction and distribution at whicl\nwe are all aiming. About that ain\nthere never has been any conflict;\nof views\n\u201cDragon Lady\u201d, Policeman Clear j\nHundred Miles Of China Coast\n\nSHANGHAI, Sept. 19.\u2014(iP)\u2014One hundred miles of the Chin'\ncoast and many offshore islands were cleared of Japanese a- /S'\npatrolled mainly by seagoing junks preparatory to the exper A\nAmerican landing\u2014through the efforts of a Chinese woman Ap5'\nrilla leader and a former Shanghai policeman. go* Jp'\nThe identity of the woman still was a secret today V w \u2018S\nis known familiarly as \u201cDragon Lady\u201d. v o\nThe man is Army Lt. Phillip Bradfield of Nashvi' ofr\nwho knew Chinese, having served with the Shanghai\nfrom 1925 to 1929.\nThe Dragon Lady decided seven years ago she coulu\nhve at peace with the Japanese in her native section in Chek. g\nProvince. She had no weapons but she did have strength and\nintelligence.\nWith two men friends she entered a Japanese town and\nknifed the sentries to obtain their guns. When she had a few\nweapons she acquired more friends who were willing to fight.\nSoon she had guerrillas operating on a wide scale in the Kiang\nnan plain.\nCongress Hands Truman\nProgram Heavy Jolting\n____4\nBRITISH CONVICT\n\u201cLORD HAW HAW\u201d\nLONDON, Sept. 19\u2014(fll-William\nJoyce, the scarfaced little Lord\nHaw Haw who broadcast Nazi pro\npaganda to the British througout\nthe war, was convicted of treason\nin Old Bailey today and sentenced\nto be hanged.\nNot a flicker of expression\ncrossed the ruddy face of the thin\nlipped defendant as Sir Frederick\nTucker, the presiding judge, had a\nblack cap placed on his wig and\npronounced the sentence.\nAc Via fiocnon/lnf] In Vtic aaII Vtr\\ur_ I\never, Joyce turned toward ac\nquaintances in the courtroom and\ngave a Nazi-type salute.\nA crowd waiting outside the\nbomb-scarred law courts cheered\nthe news. It took the jury of 10\nmen and two women, who had\nlistened for three days to argu\nments over Joyce\u2019s nationality,\nonly 20 minutes to reach a ver\ndict.\nThe blond, five-foot-four defend\nant, whose face is scarred from\nmouth to ear as the result of a\nstreet brawl, sought to evade pun\nishment by claiming American cit\nizenship on grounds that he was\nbom in Brooklyn, N. Y., 39 years\nago.\nJustice Tucker ruled today, how\never, that Joyce owed allegiance\nto the British Crown when he went\nto Germany \u201cwrapped up in the\nUnion Jack\u201d\u2014under the protection\nof a British passport obtained by\nposing as a British subject\njust before the war broke out.\nDefense solicitors, whose con\ntention that Joyce was an Ameri\ncan citizen won dismissal of two\nother counts, said they would\nappeal. The appeal probably will\nbe heard before the court of crim\ninal appeal next month.\nITALY WILL LUSt\nPORT OF TRIESTE\nLONDON, Sept. 19\u2014Iff)\u2014Foreign\nMinisters of the Big Five nations\nsaid tonight they had reached sub\nstantial agreement on the trouble,\nsome Italy-Yugoslav boundary dis\npute and had turned over to their\ndeputies the drawing of the actual\nboundary line.\nA communique issued after two\nsessions today of the Big Five\nCouncil said it had been decided\nto make Trieste, now in Italian\nhands, an international port, and\ngive each nation sovereignty over\npeoples speaking its language.\nThis solution, giving Yugoslavia\nless than she had asked and taking\nfrom Italy more than she wanted\nto give up, apparently was in line\nwith the formula proposed by So\nviet Foreign Commissar V. M.\nMolotov yesterday.\n\u201cTerritories which belong to\nCroats and Slovenes should be re\njjjrned to them. Those which are\nItalian in character, it will be prop\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 5)\nPIP yi T*\nNL./ Dionur .clcu\nARRIVES HERE AFTER\nLONG MOTOR JOURNEY\nBishop-elect Thomas H. Wright\narrived in Wilmington yesterday\nevening after a motor trip from\nSan Antonio, Texas, accompanied\nby his wife and three children and\nis staying at the home of friends\nin the city, 'it was learned last\nnight.\nDr. Wright recently resigned as\npastor of St. Mark\u2019s, church in San\nAntonio and will move into the see,\nrecently vacated by the retiring\nbishop, the Right Rev. Thomas C.\nDarst, as soon as it can be made\nready. Consecration of the new\nBishop of the Diocese of East Car\nolina will take place October 5.\nNo ceremonies have been sched\nuled until the morning of the con\nsecration, at which time high\nchurch dignitaries from through\nout the country will participate ir\nthe services. The Rt. Rev. Henrj\nI St. George Tucker, presidinf\nbishop for the Episcopal church oi\nthe United States, has been nam\ni ed as consecrator, and the bishops\ni oi Maryland, North Carolina, Lou\ni isiana and West Texas are expect\ned to attend.\nVotes To Turn USES Back\nTo States; Hits Job\nAid\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 19 \u2014OP)\nCongress handed President Tru\nman\u2019s peacetime legislative pro\ngram a couple of heavy jolts to\nday\u2014and one big boost.\nThe jolts still aren\u2019t permanent.\nBut the Senate:\nVoted 56 to 23 for putting the\nU. S. Employment Service back\nunder state management, as be\nfore the war. Mr. Truman didn\u2019t\nwant that. He said it would slow\nreconversion and handicap veter\nans and workers.\nVoted 51 to 29 against giving\nstates enough Federal money to\npay the jobless up to $25 a week.\nThe President wanted the $25.\nBut from the House Expendi\ntures committee he got something\nhe favored\u2014approval of a bill to\nlet him merge and abolish govern\nment bureaus and commissions in\nthe interests of economy and ef\nficiency.\nHouse and Senate still have to\nact on that measure.\nAnd the Senate, didn\u2019t take a\nfinai vote on the jobless pay bill.\nIt may Thursday. Then it will be\nup to the House.\nThe key provision still in the\nmeasure would let the government\ngives the states cash (MHHRMI\ntheir present jobless payments\nthrough 26 weeks. State rates vary\nfrom $15 to $28. The duration also\nvaries.\nOther top topics, on the busiest\nday of this first-post-war Congres\nsional sessions, were:\n1. Reconversion, --run employ\nment\u201d and minimum wage bills\nmoved forward.\n2. Demobilization. Congressmen\nstill want faster service discharg\nes.\n3. The Navy\u2019s peacetime size\".\nThe Admirals want a big, power\nful fleet.\nThis happened:\nReconversion\u2014\nSix hundred banner-bearing New\nYork CIO members stormed Capi\ntol Hill demanding action, about\nlike the President asked, on job\nless pay, \u2019\u2019full employment,\u201d and\na higher minimum wage.\nChairman Norton (D-NJ) of the\nHouse Labor Committee saw Mr.\nTruman. She said she \u201cleft with\nthe impression\u201d he favors raising\nfrom 40 to 65 cents an hour the\nminimum wage required of firms\nin interstate commerce. She re\nturned to the capitol, dropped in\na bill to do that.\nChairman Wagner (D-NY1 pre\ndicted the Senate Banking commit\ntee would approve Tuesday a full\nemployment bill.\nThe committee changed the bill\ntoday to say all Americans able\nand desiring to work \u2018\u2018are entitled\u201d\n(instead nf \u2018\u2018have the right\u201d) to\nan opportunity for remunerative,\nregular, full time employment.\nSenator Taft fR-Ohio) said this\n\u2018\u2018removes the fraud of fooling the\npeople\u201d about job guarantees.\nDemobilization\u2014\nThe House Republican steering\ncommittee\u2014it shapes partly policy\nin the House\u2014backed the immedi\nate release of fathers and two-year\nveterans from the armed forces.\nThe Senate Military committe\nlearned the Marines plan to cut\ntheir discharge point score below\nthe present 70 as soon as possible.\nThe Navy\nSecretary Torrestal plunked be\nfore the House Naval committee\na bill to authorize a peacetime\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 3)\nBowles To Ask Congress For Power To Control\nPrice Of New Homes To Avoid Inflationary Boom\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 19 \u2014UtI\u2014\nPrice Administrator Chester\nBowles said today he will ask Con\ngress for authority to control the\nprice of new homes \"to avoid a\nserious inflationary boom in this\nBowles also announced in a\nstatement, which he amplified at\na news conference, that he in\ntended to put into effect a pro\ngram sharply tightening OPA\u2019s\ncontrol over building material\nprices. These controls also will\ncover most of the fixtures and\nhousehold equipment which go in\nto a new home, and construction\nservices.\n1\nRegional and district OPA of\nfices throughout the country will\nprepare specific dollars-and-cents\nprices on as many items as pos\nible, Bowles said.\nDescribing the whole field of\nhome building, home ownership\nand rent control as \u201ca highly ex\nplosive situation,\u201d Bowles said:\n\u201cUnless the real estate interests,\nthe home building industry and the\npublic join with the government\nto meet the issue head-on, the dan\nger of inflation in this all-im\nportant field will grow rapidly.\n\"If we fail to handle this pro\nblem with courage and good judg-j\nment, we\u2019re inviting a repetition\nof the real estate and home build\ning \u201cboom\u201d and \u201cbust\u201d experi\nence which helped to b ring on the\ncollapse of 1929.\u201d\nBowles said the OPA program\nwould include elimination of rent\ncontrols only when the danger of\na general increase in an area has\nbeen eliminated\u2014when the normal\nbargaining situation between land\nlord and tenant has been restored.\nHe said rent controls would be nec\nessary through June, 1946 in most\nof the medium and large industrial\nareas.\nAs for building materials, he\ntimated that their cost has risen\n3 percent since 1939, and called\nmany of the 1939 prices \"too hijjh\nfor large volume home construe*\ntion.\nNew dollars-and-cents prices will\ncover lumber, insulation, brick,\nsoil pipe, millwork items, such as\ndoors windows and cabinets, as\nwell as bathtubs, septic tanks and\nwash basins.\nThere will also be ceilings for\npainting and papering, renewing of\nroof, installing plumbing, dig\ning cellars, etc.\nk\n,Hundreds Moved As Cape Fear\nmakes 2 Lives, Damages Homes;\nMacArthur Closes Nippon Times\nx\n<r\nJap Leaders\nClean House\nOf Suspects\nMACARTHUR SILENT\nOccupation Work Moving\nSmoothly Headquarters\nReports\nTOKYO Thursday, Sept. 20\nUP) \u2014The Japanese cabinet\nwill soon clean out more of\nits war time leaders, reliable\ninformants predicted, in keep\ning with the hard fisted Allied\noccupation controls which tem\nporarily shut down another\nTokyo newspaper.\nAmerican headquarters mean\nwhile announced that a new and\nlonger list of Japanese to be ques\ntioned on war guilt charges would\nbe issued soon, supplementing the\nfirst list which contained 47 names.\nGood news to American service\nmen in the Pacific with sufficient\ndischarge points came in a Pearl\nHarbor Navy Headquarters an\nnouncement that huge \u201cCarrier Di\nvision 24,\u2019\u2019 composed of the Navy\u2019s\nbiggest flattoo. the Saratoga, and\n25 escort carriers, is being formed\nto transport 20,000 or more men\nhome each month.\nReliable Nipponese sources\nwhich forecast more resignations\nfrom Premier Prince Higashi\niK>\u00abi*\u00bb cabinet placed Vice Pre\nmier Prince Fumimaro Konoye\u2019s\nname at the head of the list of\nthose to go out. Konoye, twice Pre\nmier of Japan, headed the govern\nment when Japan invaded China in\n1937.\nOthers mentioned were Lt. Gen.\nToshishiro Obata and Taketora\nOgata, ministers without protfolio.\nOgata, also chief cabinet sec\nretary, whose name was among\nmembers of the Jingoist Black\nDragon Society listed among Gen\neral MacArthur\u2019s selection of sus\npected war criminals.\nMamoru Shigemitsu Foreign\nMinister in two of Japan\u2019s war\ncabinets, resigned from that same\npost on Premier Higashi-Kuni's\ngovernment two days ago, his\nplace being taken by Shigeru Yo\nshida, a peace advocate.\nHigashi-Kuni, who told a recent\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 4)\nHORROR STORIES\nMOUNT IN COURT\nLUENEBERG, GERMANY,\nSept. 19\u2014(JF)\u2014In the clipped, re\nstrained testimony of British offi\ncers, five military judges trying\nJosef Kramer and 44 co-defendants\nfor mass murder today heard de\nscriptions of new horrors of the\nBelsen concentration camp Kra\nmer commanded.\nKramer and all but one of the\nguards who served under him lost\ntheir impassivity as the story, its\nsensational nature contrasting\nsharply with the quiet manner of\nits presentation went into the rec\nord.\nOnly Irma Grese, 21 year old\nblonde who was Kramer\u2019s chiei\nwoman guard, managed to main\ntain the defiant, contemptuous look\nthat marred her undeniable good\nlooks.\nThe prosecution told the story\ntoday of:\n1. A water supply system at Bel\nsen consisting of five concrete vats\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 7)\nCivilians Lining Up For Food In Jap Capital\nA group of Jap civilians line up at one of the m any food distribution points in Tokyo to receive their\nrations from American troops. The task of feeding th ousands of bombed-out Nipponese is one of the big\nproblems confronting our occupation forces now spreading throughout Japan. (International Soundphoto)\nForts Complete Japan-Capital Hop;\nU. S. Airlines Plan 300 MPH Flights\n\nTranscontinental T o In\naugurate 14-Hour Trip.\n(By The Associated Press)\nThe speed flight of three Army\nB-29\u2019s from Japan to the United\nStates coincided yesterday with an\nnouncements by three commercial\nairlines that they hoped to step up\npassenger transportation to a 300\nmiles-an-hour level soon.\nTranscontinental and Western\nAir said it hoped to become the\nfirst 300-mile-an-hour airline and\nplanned to inaugurate a 14-hour\nNew York to Europe service with\nin a few weeks.\nPan American World Airways\nsaid it was adding 118 new flights\nto its Latin American division\nschedules and had plans for using\n300-miles-an-hour craft that would\ncarry as many as 204 passengers.\nThe company said new planes now\non order would make possible an\n11-hour New York to London ser\nvice. It said it was aiming later\nat 400-mile-an-hour speeds.\nEastern Air Lines announced\nthrough its president, Capt, Eddie\nRickenbacker, that it had signed\ncontracts for 20 new-engined plan\nes that would cut the company\u2019s\nschedules from New York to\n(Continued on Page Two; Col, 5)\nPILOT LIGHT CAUSES\nFATAL BLAST DURING\nSUICIDE ATTEMPT\nPHILADELPHIA, Sept. 19\u2014W\nA pilot light on a gas refrigerator\nignited fumes escaping from a\nstove and blew out the side of a\nhouse while a jilted suitor was\ncommitting suicide by gas, detec\ntive George Marker said today.\nCharles G. Littleton, 28, was\nfound dead on the floor of his two\nroom apartment by Marker, who\nwas called to investigate the blast\nlast night. The detective said an\nautopsy will be made to determine\nwhether death was caused by gas\nor the explosion.\nMarker said Littleton\u2019s girl\nfriend had broken off their engage\nment a short time before.\nNavy To Close N. C.\nPre-Flight School\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 19.\u2014(ff)\n\u2014The Navy announced today\nthe early closing of pre-flight\ntraining schools for prospec\ntive Naval aviators at the Uni\nversity of Georgia and the Uni\nversity of North Carolina.\nThe school at the University\nof Georgia will close with the\ntermination of the present\nclass October 1, and the Uni\nversity of North Carolina school\nwill close with the present cfess\non October 15.\nS' CKEN YOUTHS\nW FOR FUT1 E\nSALISBURY, N. C., Sept. 19.\u2014\nIff)\u2014Three young brothers ate\nheartily today of chocolate cake\nand ice cream and, like boys all\nover the world, talked of what they\nintend to do when they \u201cgrow up.\u201d\nBut these boys won\u2019t grow up.\nAll are totally disabled from in\ncurable Muscular Dystrophy and\ntheir widowed mother, Mrs. D.\nE. Pinion, said today that\u2014con\ntrary to earlier reports\u2014the boys\ndo not know that medical science\nis unable to help their, plight and\nthey are doomed to an early death.\nToday, the boys David, 19,\nBilly, 15, and Lloyd, 12\u2014 shared\nthe bewildered delight of their\nmother in the words of cheer a .d\ngifts which flooded their home here.\nThe family misfortunes were known\nin this section, general knowledge\nof their plight became known to\nthe world only, with a story and\nphotograph circulated by news\nservices early this week.\nFirst response\u2014and, from the\nboys\u2019 standpoint, one of the most\nappreciated was a mammoth\nhome-made chocolate cake, with\nice cream, brought to their home\nearly today.\nSince then, a constant flow of\ngifts and messages has been re\nceived. The Salisbury Lions Club\n(Continned on Page Two; Col. 5)\nFly Last Leg Of Trip In\nLittle Over Two Elap\nsed Hours\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 19.\u2014(IP)\u2014\nThree B-29\u2019s completed tonight\nthe first flight direct from Japan\nto the capital, but failed to make\nit nonstop because of unexpeced\nheadwinds.\n\u201cWe hit weather you wouldn\u2019t\nhit once in 50 times,\u201d declared Lt.\nGen. Barney M. Giles, leader of\nthe Superfortress flight which\nlanded at National Airport shortly\nbefore 10 p. m. EWT.\nTired and disappointed, but far\nfrom downhearted, Giles declared\nthe same trip would be made\nnonstop many times in the future.\nThe three huge ships flew nearly\n7,000 miles from the Island of\nHokkaido, stopping to refuel at\nChicago.\nGiles disclosed that they landed\nat Chicago 'with from 100 to 1,200\ngallons of gasoline in their tanks,\nbut had chosen not to take any\nchances with the big planes.\n\u201cThis was a practical test, not\na stunt,\u201d Giles said.\nThe three mighty bombers, strip\nped of the guns which they had\ncarried into compat over Japan,\nleft Mizutani Airfield near Sap\nporo, capital of the northernmost\nof the Japanese main islands, at\napproximately 4 p. m., Eastern\nWar Time, Tuesday, and reached\nChicago around 6 p. m. (EWT)\ntoday.\nThey flew on to Washington in\njust over two hours.\nGen. H. H. Arnold, Army Air\nforce chief who was among the\nscore of more of Generals wait\ning to greet the three 12-man\ncrews, said the flight was made\ntn see \u201ciust what we mieht ex\npect from an airplane of this\ntype..\n\u201cI think we found out quite a\nbit,\u201d he said. \u201cWe found out, at\nleast, that we can fly from Japan\nto Chicago with headwinds all\nthe way.\u201d\nGiles said that the worst head\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 6)\nATTLEE TELLS INDIA\nSELF-GOVERNMENT TO\nBE FORTHCOMING SOON\nLONDON, Sept. 19.\u2014W\u2014Prime\nMinister Attlee told India tonight\nthat positive steps would be taken\nimmediately after the forthcoming\nIndian elections to give the sub\ncontinent full self government.\nHe spoke by radio to both India\nand Great Britain, amplifying\nearlier remarks by Lord Wavell,\nthe Viceroy.\n\u201cThe first step is to get as soon\nas may be as demcratic a repre\nsentation of the Indian peoples as\npossible,\u201d Attlee said.\nHe said elections of Central and\nProvincial legislators would be\nheld this winter and followed \u201cby\npositive steps to set up a constitu\nent assembly of Indian-elected re\npresentatives charged with the\ntask of framing a new constitu\ntion.\u201d\ncvavubco A11 UAC O A AAlwl J UX IUU\nFayetteville Light Infantry and in\nschQ.pl buildings.\nPeople working in Fayetteville\nhaving homes outside the city, had\nalready crowded hotels to capaci*/\nfor the last three days, officers\nsaid, necessitating the use of the\nimpromptu shelters.\nAuthorities, predicting heavy wa\nter damage in the flooded sections\nof the city said that the river stage\nat Fayetteville had reached slight\nly over 66 feet and was expected to\nrise to 67 feet sometime last night\nwith gradually receding waters fol\nlowing.\nThe Atlantic Coast Line railroad\nbridge leading into Fayetteville\nwas the setting when a bit of his\ntory repeated itself as the ACL\nplaced freight cars on the trestle\nto hold it down. The only other time\nsuch a drastic move had been nec\nessary was in August of 1908, when\nthe Cape Fear reached a record\nheight of over 68 feet.\nSchool children in Fayetteville\nwere dismissed yesterday and no\nestimate could be obtained as to\nhow long school activities would\nbe suspended.\nAt Rockingham, authorities re\nported that the Bluett Falls dam,\nwhich had been expected to break,\nhad held back the flood waters\ncollecting behind it and that danger\nto the area appeared diminishing\nwith waters receding gradually.\nTraffic has been resumed on p*\u00bbc\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 3).\nARGENTINES DEFY\nREGIME OF PERON\nBUENOS AIRES. Sept. 19\u2014(P)\u2014\nThousands of Argentines marching\nthrough this capital\u2019s streets today\nin a gigantic demonstration for\n\u2018constitution and liberty\u2019' shouted\ndefiance of Col. Juan Peron\u2019s mili\ntary government.\nShouts of \u2018\u2018down with Peron,\u201d\n\u2018down with despotism\u2019 and\n\u2018death to dictatorship\" arose fre\nquently from the crowd but, up to\nmid-afternoon, the \u201cdisorders and\nperhaps a struggle\" Peron had\npredicted last night had not oc\ncurred. Peron is vice-president and\nstrong man of the government.\nA threat of trouble was averted\nwhen armed police, acting on the\ncomplaint of two anti-Peron law\nyers, raided headquarters of the\npro-government Nationalist Youth\nAlliance just before the parade\nstarted and emerged with rifles,\nhand-grenades and powder.\nHeavy detachments of police and\nshock troops stood ready with\ntrucks, rifles and tear gas bombs\nto control any outbreak, and busi\nness houses ran down their heavy\niron shutters.\nHowever, the multitudes which\nbegan pouring from offices, fac\ntories and shops soon after noon\nseemed in good humor.\nThe assembly was called for 2:30\np.m. local time (1:30 EWT). Fif\nteen minutes later the four wide\n(Continued on Page Two; Qol. 1)\nRed Cross,\nFolice Aid\nResidents\nBLUETT DAM HOLDS\nHighways In Eastern Sec*\ntion Of State Closed\nBy Floods\nRampaging Cape Fear river we*\nters which reportedly took the lives\nof two Negro youths in the Fayette*\nville area were inundating low-iy.\ning sections of the city necessitate\ning evacuation of several hundr. 1\npersons, according to police there.\nThe drowned boys were Johnnie\nC. Holmes, 12, and Sidney Johnson,\n16. Police said Holmes was drown*\ned while playing in the water on\nthe Cedar Creek road near Fayette*\nville and Johnson was drowned on\nhigh water of the river road.\nA third drowning had been re\nported but police said that a check\nfailed to yield any confirmation at\na late hour last night.\nThe evacuation, which was oe*\ngun early yesterday morning, was\nbeing carried on by police, the Red\nCross, soldiers from Fort Bragg\nand volunteer workers.\nField kitchens have been set up\nand relief workers were placing\nevacuees in the armory of the","height":"27520","width":"20784"}}
